04499nam a22005055i 9780226412351DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t20122012ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a9780226412351  a(DE-B1597)523816  a(OCoLC)812924947  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aBL2207.3b.J67 2012 7aREL0000002bisacsh04a322/.10952090342231 aStorm, Jason Ananda Josephson, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Invention of Religion in Japan /cJason Ananda Josephson Storm. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2012] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (404 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tA Note on Texts and Translations -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Marks of Heresy: Organizing Difference in Premodern Japan -- t2. Heretical Anthropology -- t3. The Arrival of Religion -- t4. The Science of the Gods -- t5. Formations of the Shinto Secular -- t6. Taming Demons -- t7. Inventing Japanese Religion -- t8. Religion within the Limits -- tConclusion -- tAppendix: Religion Explained -- tNotes -- tCharacter Glossary -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThroughout its long history, Japan had no concept of what we call “religion.” There was no corresponding Japanese word, nor anything close to its meaning. But when American warships appeared off the coast of Japan in 1853 and forced the Japanese government to sign treaties demanding, among other things, freedom of religion, the country had to contend with this Western idea. In this book, Jason Ananda Josephson reveals how Japanese officials invented religion in Japan and traces the sweeping intellectual, legal, and cultural changes that followed. More than a tale of oppression or hegemony, Josephson’s account demonstrates that the process of articulating religion offered the Japanese state a valuable opportunity. In addition to carving out space for belief in Christianity and certain forms of Buddhism, Japanese officials excluded Shinto from the category. Instead, they enshrined it as a national ideology while relegating the popular practices of indigenous shamans and female mediums to the category of “superstitions”—and thus beyond the sphere of tolerance. Josephson argues that the invention of religion in Japan was a politically charged, boundary-drawing exercise that not only extensively reclassified the inherited materials of Buddhism, Confucianism, and Shinto to lasting effect, but also reshaped, in subtle but significant ways, our own formulation of the concept of religion today. This ambitious and wide-ranging book contributes an important perspective to broader debates on the nature of religion, the secular, science, and superstition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aReligion and statezJapanxHistoryy19th century. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  areligious studies, faith, belief, asia, eastern world, east, asian, japanese, worship, holy, 1800s, america, american, colonization, war, wartime, warship, treaties, treaty, politics, political, western, freedom, intellectual, change, social, culture, cultural, oppression, hegemony, christian, christianity, buddhism, shinto, superstition, tolerance, confucianism, international, global, academic, scholarly, research.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022641233740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226412351423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226412351/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles